00:02:53.150 --> 00:02:58.060
So today is the final
lecture on feedback.

00:02:58.060 --> 00:03:00.910
What we've done over the
course of the last week

00:03:00.910 --> 00:03:03.730
and a half or so is looked
at a variety of applications.

00:03:03.730 --> 00:03:06.100
Last time we looked
at how to perform--

00:03:06.100 --> 00:03:07.900
how to improve
performance with feedback.

00:03:07.900 --> 00:03:10.316
We looked at how you could
increase the bandwidth of an op

00:03:10.316 --> 00:03:13.390
amp, increase the
speed of an op amp,

00:03:13.390 --> 00:03:16.780
change a motor so that
its natural output, which

00:03:16.780 --> 00:03:18.790
is a voltage
controlled velocity,

00:03:18.790 --> 00:03:21.580
could be perturbed into a
voltage controlled position.

00:03:21.580 --> 00:03:23.740
Today I want to just
do a few more examples.

00:03:23.740 --> 00:03:26.590
Because what I want you to do
is leave this place thinking

00:03:26.590 --> 00:03:28.480
feedback's really useful.

00:03:28.480 --> 00:03:29.680
It's not just torture.

00:03:29.680 --> 00:03:30.736
I mean it is torture.

00:03:30.736 --> 00:03:32.860
We do torture you and you're
supposed to figure out

00:03:32.860 --> 00:03:34.568
how it works quantitatively
and all that.

00:03:34.568 --> 00:03:36.010
But it's not just torture.

00:03:36.010 --> 00:03:37.870
It's actually very useful.

00:03:37.870 --> 00:03:41.800
And that's what I
want you to take away.

00:03:41.800 --> 00:03:44.650
The first application today
that I want to think about

00:03:44.650 --> 00:03:47.390
is reducing unwanted
parameter variation.

00:03:47.390 --> 00:03:50.140
So the idea that I
want you to think about

00:03:50.140 --> 00:03:53.590
is what do you have in a power
amplifier of the type that you

00:03:53.590 --> 00:03:55.900
would drive speakers--

00:03:55.900 --> 00:03:58.270
of the type that you would
use to drive speakers.

00:03:58.270 --> 00:04:01.090
That's a kind of a
complicated electronic device.

00:04:01.090 --> 00:04:03.250
It's kind of hard
to make high power.

00:04:03.250 --> 00:04:05.500
You end up having to
generate high power in order

00:04:05.500 --> 00:04:10.517
to make a loud speaker that
fills this hall for example.

00:04:10.517 --> 00:04:12.100
And if you were to
try to do something

00:04:12.100 --> 00:04:14.935
bigger like a concert,
it's even harder.

00:04:14.935 --> 00:04:17.050
And the problem with
those kinds of devices

00:04:17.050 --> 00:04:19.779
is that they are active.

00:04:19.779 --> 00:04:21.370
They generate signals
that are bigger

00:04:21.370 --> 00:04:23.560
that generate more
power at their output

00:04:23.560 --> 00:04:25.870
than there was
available at the input.

00:04:25.870 --> 00:04:28.280
And we're very good
at such things.

00:04:28.280 --> 00:04:32.260
Unfortunately, such things
are intrinsically non-linear.

00:04:32.260 --> 00:04:36.430
So we actually take advantage
of non-linearities in materials

00:04:36.430 --> 00:04:38.030
in order to do that.

00:04:38.030 --> 00:04:40.000
The result though is
that at a high level

00:04:40.000 --> 00:04:41.350
the thing's still non-linear.

00:04:41.350 --> 00:04:43.720
And we can see some of that.

00:04:43.720 --> 00:04:46.120
And not only non-linear,
but other things.

00:04:46.120 --> 00:04:48.480
They can be
temperature dependent.

00:04:48.480 --> 00:04:50.560
So if you were to make
a high power amplifier

00:04:50.560 --> 00:04:52.540
it's very likely
that the performance

00:04:52.540 --> 00:04:55.270
would depend on temperature.

00:04:55.270 --> 00:04:57.090
Who cares, it's always
room temperature.

00:04:57.090 --> 00:05:00.310
No, not inside the amplifier.

00:05:00.310 --> 00:05:02.050
It may start out
at room temperature

00:05:02.050 --> 00:05:04.300
every time you turn it on,
but within a few minutes

00:05:04.300 --> 00:05:06.200
it's going to be much higher
than room temperature.

00:05:06.200 --> 00:05:07.866
And if you didn't do
something about it,

00:05:07.866 --> 00:05:10.730
the gain would change.

00:05:10.730 --> 00:05:13.280
If you didn't do something
about it in your car,

00:05:13.280 --> 00:05:15.500
it would track the
weather, which may be good.

00:05:15.500 --> 00:05:17.530
Maybe it would
provide a distraction

00:05:17.530 --> 00:05:18.980
and provide utility to winter.

00:05:18.980 --> 00:05:21.740
But short of that
normally we don't

00:05:21.740 --> 00:05:25.940
want the sound level that
comes out of a stereo system

00:05:25.940 --> 00:05:28.380
to depend on temperature.

00:05:28.380 --> 00:05:30.770
So how do you take a
device that intrinsically

00:05:30.770 --> 00:05:31.980
depends on temperature?

00:05:31.980 --> 00:05:34.580
Here I am imagining that I
have a power amplifier whose

00:05:34.580 --> 00:05:38.600
gain can go between 8
and 12, say, depending

00:05:38.600 --> 00:05:40.340
on what the temperature is.

00:05:40.340 --> 00:05:43.040
How could you fix that
so that its behavior

00:05:43.040 --> 00:05:47.570
was more consistent from day
to day, from hour to hour.

00:05:47.570 --> 00:05:50.480
And of course, not too
surprisingly, the answer

00:05:50.480 --> 00:05:53.272
is use feedback.

00:05:53.272 --> 00:05:54.920
So how do you do that?

00:05:54.920 --> 00:05:57.800
So you want to connect the
amplifier to the speaker.

00:05:57.800 --> 00:05:59.847
After all, it's
inside the amplifier

00:05:59.847 --> 00:06:01.430
that you have all
the transistors that

00:06:01.430 --> 00:06:03.020
are able to drive the speaker.

00:06:03.020 --> 00:06:06.790
So you don't want to
perturb that connection.

00:06:06.790 --> 00:06:08.280
But what you can
do with feedback

00:06:08.280 --> 00:06:12.180
is monitor what was the voltage
that actually got produced

00:06:12.180 --> 00:06:15.020
and try to rig the feedback
system to coerce it

00:06:15.020 --> 00:06:18.410
to the voltage you wish it were.

00:06:18.410 --> 00:06:21.180
So the way you can do that is
to generate a feedback loop.

00:06:21.180 --> 00:06:26.130
Precede the power amplifier
with a voltage amplifier

00:06:26.130 --> 00:06:28.890
that does not necessarily
significantly increase

00:06:28.890 --> 00:06:29.400
the power.

00:06:29.400 --> 00:06:31.566
That makes that kind of an
amplifier somewhat easier

00:06:31.566 --> 00:06:34.400
to make.

00:06:34.400 --> 00:06:36.860
So imagine that
this power amplifier

00:06:36.860 --> 00:06:38.720
has big chunky
transistors because it

00:06:38.720 --> 00:06:43.160
has to generate amps in order
to make your speakers work.

00:06:43.160 --> 00:06:46.460
This, by comparison, could be
a much less power hungry kind

00:06:46.460 --> 00:06:47.060
of amplifier.

00:06:47.060 --> 00:06:48.850
And it's easier to
make, and in particular

00:06:48.850 --> 00:06:51.260
would be easy to make it
with a gain of 10 or 100

00:06:51.260 --> 00:06:52.730
or 1,000 or 10,000.

00:06:52.730 --> 00:06:56.270
We're very good at doing
that kind of stuff.

00:06:56.270 --> 00:07:00.440
Then the idea of feedback
is to compare the signal

00:07:00.440 --> 00:07:04.490
that you generated to the signal
that you might have desired.

00:07:04.490 --> 00:07:06.080
So here's the signal
you generated.

00:07:06.080 --> 00:07:07.430
Here is the signal you desired.

00:07:07.430 --> 00:07:09.650
I'm comparing it
through a monitor

00:07:09.650 --> 00:07:14.710
that's feeding back beta
times the output voltage.

00:07:14.710 --> 00:07:16.750
The reason I do that
can be seen if you just

00:07:16.750 --> 00:07:17.666
work through the math.

00:07:17.666 --> 00:07:21.700
So if I just write the
closed loop transfer function

00:07:21.700 --> 00:07:27.890
for x goes to y, the easy
way to think about that's

00:07:27.890 --> 00:07:29.630
Black's formula,
of course, right?

00:07:29.630 --> 00:07:33.500
So think about the forward
path, k times f naught divided

00:07:33.500 --> 00:07:35.580
by 1 plus the loop gain.

00:07:35.580 --> 00:07:42.342
So 1 plus the gain around
the loop is beta k f naught.

00:07:42.342 --> 00:07:43.800
And now just think
about what would

00:07:43.800 --> 00:07:47.280
happen if I coerced it so
that I made k the thing that's

00:07:47.280 --> 00:07:51.230
under my control big.

00:07:51.230 --> 00:07:53.750
If I make k big
enough, then I can

00:07:53.750 --> 00:07:57.660
arrange so that beta k f naught,
independent of beta and k,

00:07:57.660 --> 00:08:00.110
I can always choose k so
that the product is big

00:08:00.110 --> 00:08:03.600
compared to the one.

00:08:03.600 --> 00:08:07.460
If I do that, I
can ignore the one.

00:08:07.460 --> 00:08:09.650
If I ignore the
one, the k's cancel,

00:08:09.650 --> 00:08:13.100
the f naughts cancel, and
I'm left with whatever beta.

00:08:13.100 --> 00:08:15.170
Beta didn't depend on f naught.

00:08:15.170 --> 00:08:18.230
That's what I wanted.

00:08:18.230 --> 00:08:22.390
It didn't even depend
on k, other than k

00:08:22.390 --> 00:08:25.960
had to be big enough so
that the division worked.

00:08:25.960 --> 00:08:32.110
So the result is that you
can make a stable gain

00:08:32.110 --> 00:08:35.799
by incorporating an amplifier
with an unstable gain.

00:08:35.799 --> 00:08:38.080
Unstable meaning that it
varies in time, not that it's

00:08:38.080 --> 00:08:40.496
unstable in the sense that we
often use the word unstable.

00:08:40.496 --> 00:08:41.350
I should avoid that.

00:08:41.350 --> 00:08:43.630
The parameter of
the gain changes.

00:08:43.630 --> 00:08:46.300
It changes between 8 and 12.

00:08:46.300 --> 00:08:48.740
And I can illustrate that
with this kind of a picture.

00:08:48.740 --> 00:08:52.840
If I plot the
variation at f naught.

00:08:52.840 --> 00:08:54.850
I've showed a range
here from 0 to 20.

00:08:54.850 --> 00:08:57.220
I'm imagining that in
a practical situation

00:08:57.220 --> 00:09:00.850
it could vary between 8 and 12.

00:09:00.850 --> 00:09:03.880
And then in red,
I'm showing the gain

00:09:03.880 --> 00:09:07.850
that would result if
there were no feedback.

00:09:07.850 --> 00:09:11.770
And as you can see that
over the range of 8 to 12,

00:09:11.770 --> 00:09:15.700
the output gain, the
total gain of the system,

00:09:15.700 --> 00:09:17.710
varies between 8 and
12, not surprisingly.

00:09:17.710 --> 00:09:19.720
That's what it would
mean to have no feedback.

00:09:19.720 --> 00:09:25.270
But if I crank in feedback, if
I set the k to 100 and feedback

00:09:25.270 --> 00:09:30.820
ratio to 1/10, the 100 is
sufficient to make the one

00:09:30.820 --> 00:09:34.660
negligible which means that
my overall gain is 1 over 10

00:09:34.660 --> 00:09:37.780
determined only by the
feedback ratio, beta.

00:09:37.780 --> 00:09:41.050
And so the result
is this line shows

00:09:41.050 --> 00:09:44.830
the solution to that equation.

00:09:44.830 --> 00:09:47.850
And you can see that
it's ruler straight

00:09:47.850 --> 00:09:50.370
through the interesting region.

00:09:50.370 --> 00:09:51.540
Does that makes sense?

00:09:51.540 --> 00:09:54.090
So what I've been able
to do is use feedback

00:09:54.090 --> 00:09:57.240
in order to control the
value of a parameter that

00:09:57.240 --> 00:10:00.480
was otherwise variable,
or sensitive to something,

00:10:00.480 --> 00:10:01.590
often temperature.

00:10:01.590 --> 00:10:04.020
Is that all clear?

00:10:04.020 --> 00:10:07.110
That kind of a thing--

00:10:07.110 --> 00:10:09.150
Question?

00:10:09.150 --> 00:10:12.891
I got rid of all the
variations, except beta.

00:10:12.891 --> 00:10:14.140
What about variations in beta?

00:10:16.970 --> 00:10:19.247
Right, the premise was
I couldn't control this,

00:10:19.247 --> 00:10:20.830
it was going to vary
between 8 and 12.

00:10:20.830 --> 00:10:23.120
But what if beta changes.

00:10:23.120 --> 00:10:25.550
What if beta went
from 1/8th to 1/12th,

00:10:25.550 --> 00:10:28.960
would that affect things?

00:10:28.960 --> 00:10:30.675
AUDIENCE: So yeah,
so we could put

00:10:30.675 --> 00:10:31.900
a feedback loop [INAUDIBLE].

00:10:31.900 --> 00:10:34.191
DENNIS FREEMAN: You could
put in another feedback loop.

00:10:34.191 --> 00:10:37.510
That doesn't sound like it's
going to converge quickly.

00:10:37.510 --> 00:10:38.824
Yes?

00:10:38.824 --> 00:10:42.185
AUDIENCE: Typically we want to
be able to control beta anyway.

00:10:42.185 --> 00:10:43.060
DENNIS FREEMAN: Right

00:10:43.060 --> 00:10:44.240
AUDIENCE: There's
nothing users control.

00:10:44.240 --> 00:10:45.790
DENNIS FREEMAN: That's right,
we'd want to control it.

00:10:45.790 --> 00:10:46.950
Is there any reason we--

00:10:46.950 --> 00:10:48.520
but that's what we wanted
to do with f naught too.

00:10:48.520 --> 00:10:49.603
We wanted to control that.

00:10:49.603 --> 00:10:51.730
We'd like that to be 10.

00:10:51.730 --> 00:10:52.700
Yes.

00:10:52.700 --> 00:10:56.095
AUDIENCE: It will depend on
how that beta would change.

00:10:56.095 --> 00:10:58.520
Changes, say, from
1/8th to 1/12th,

00:10:58.520 --> 00:10:59.975
probably nothing to worry about.

00:10:59.975 --> 00:11:04.957
If it changes from
1/8th to 1 over 8,000,

00:11:04.957 --> 00:11:07.739
then you may want to think
about what k and f are.

00:11:07.739 --> 00:11:09.780
DENNIS FREEMAN: So what
do you think will happen?

00:11:09.780 --> 00:11:11.571
Do you think it will
vary a lot or a little

00:11:11.571 --> 00:11:13.590
compared to 8 to 12?

00:11:13.590 --> 00:11:14.970
AUDIENCE: Probably
not that much.

00:11:14.970 --> 00:11:15.930
DENNIS FREEMAN: Why?

00:11:15.930 --> 00:11:18.602
AUDIENCE: Because
the k is already--

00:11:18.602 --> 00:11:21.506
1/8th and 1/12th is not
really much of a difference

00:11:21.506 --> 00:11:22.357
in terms of--

00:11:22.357 --> 00:11:24.690
DENNIS FREEMAN: So why do I
think about beta differently

00:11:24.690 --> 00:11:27.650
from the way I think
about f naught?

00:11:27.650 --> 00:11:30.950
Is there a good reason
for that or is that just

00:11:30.950 --> 00:11:32.810
wishful thinking, right?

00:11:32.810 --> 00:11:34.230
Engineering by wishful thinking.

00:11:34.230 --> 00:11:36.320
I wish I could get a beta
that was exactly right.

00:11:36.320 --> 00:11:38.135
Yes?

00:11:38.135 --> 00:11:41.105
AUDIENCE: For amplification,
beta needs to be less than 1

00:11:41.105 --> 00:11:44.060
[INAUDIBLE] so [INAUDIBLE]
the resistor, it's not

00:11:44.060 --> 00:11:46.060
going to have a very big
temperature [INAUDIBLE]

00:11:46.060 --> 00:11:47.390
DENNIS FREEMAN: Precisely.

00:11:47.390 --> 00:11:52.150
So the problem is getting
gain in a stable and reliable

00:11:52.150 --> 00:11:56.360
fashion, not in
getting attenuation.

00:11:56.360 --> 00:12:02.370
We can control the value of a
resistor with great precision.

00:12:02.370 --> 00:12:05.490
And so it's easy,
by comparison, it's

00:12:05.490 --> 00:12:12.310
relatively easy to control the
gain of a resistor network,

00:12:12.310 --> 00:12:17.140
and much harder to control the
gain of a transistor network.

00:12:17.140 --> 00:12:19.150
Transistors have gain.

00:12:19.150 --> 00:12:22.870
Gain is hard to make in a non
temperature dependent fashion.

00:12:22.870 --> 00:12:25.990
Division by a resistor, it's
not hard to make a resistor.

00:12:25.990 --> 00:12:28.810
I mean it's not trivial,
but it's not hard.

00:12:28.810 --> 00:12:32.020
Even in the dark ages--

00:12:32.020 --> 00:12:35.980
even in the dark ages, resistors
were made by winding wires,

00:12:35.980 --> 00:12:37.750
and they were very
stable with temperature

00:12:37.750 --> 00:12:41.080
or could be made to be very
stable with temperatures.

00:12:41.080 --> 00:12:45.460
So one of the tricks in
feedback is that we usually--

00:12:45.460 --> 00:12:47.500
so we move the--

00:12:47.500 --> 00:12:52.120
we move the parameter dependence
out of the forward path

00:12:52.120 --> 00:12:55.330
and into the feedback
path with the idea

00:12:55.330 --> 00:12:57.310
that we're moving it
out of the part that

00:12:57.310 --> 00:13:00.550
has active parts like
transistors and into the part

00:13:00.550 --> 00:13:02.920
that we can build
with passive parts.

00:13:02.920 --> 00:13:05.040
And we almost always
do feedback that way.

00:13:05.040 --> 00:13:06.290
Not always, but almost always.

00:13:09.200 --> 00:13:11.930
Another important point
is that this could

00:13:11.930 --> 00:13:15.320
work at a very high speed.

00:13:15.320 --> 00:13:17.270
As an illustration
of that I want

00:13:17.270 --> 00:13:22.160
to think about what would be
inside of that f naught box.

00:13:22.160 --> 00:13:23.900
Here's a very
simple idea of what

00:13:23.900 --> 00:13:27.770
you could put in there that's
based on two power transistors.

00:13:27.770 --> 00:13:30.040
This is not a course
in power transistors.

00:13:30.040 --> 00:13:32.060
I am not going to give
you a very good model

00:13:32.060 --> 00:13:32.810
for a transistor.

00:13:32.810 --> 00:13:34.851
There's other courses that
do much better justice

00:13:34.851 --> 00:13:36.300
to that topic.

00:13:36.300 --> 00:13:38.270
But what I do want to
say is that the idea

00:13:38.270 --> 00:13:41.030
would be that turning those
transistors on and off

00:13:41.030 --> 00:13:43.370
represents a significant
source of distortion,

00:13:43.370 --> 00:13:45.420
or potentially a
source of distortion.

00:13:45.420 --> 00:13:48.140
So for example, the
simplest possible model

00:13:48.140 --> 00:13:51.860
I could think about
would say that in order

00:13:51.860 --> 00:13:54.740
to generate, in order to
push this voltage to a higher

00:13:54.740 --> 00:13:59.600
number, what I want to do
is turn this transistor on

00:13:59.600 --> 00:14:01.760
because this will
pull this voltage up

00:14:01.760 --> 00:14:04.470
toward the positive rail.

00:14:04.470 --> 00:14:07.110
So if the input is such
that I'd like this to go up

00:14:07.110 --> 00:14:09.570
what I would like to have
happen is that this transistor

00:14:09.570 --> 00:14:12.900
would come on and conduct
current this way, which would

00:14:12.900 --> 00:14:15.930
suck this voltage up to there.

00:14:15.930 --> 00:14:20.130
To do that, the voltage here
has to exceed the voltage there.

00:14:20.130 --> 00:14:23.590
For a BJT, that's not the
only kind of transistor

00:14:23.590 --> 00:14:26.950
I'm just illustrating one
particular kind of example.

00:14:26.950 --> 00:14:31.780
For a bipolar
transistor of this type,

00:14:31.780 --> 00:14:33.660
the way you would turn
that transistor on

00:14:33.660 --> 00:14:35.880
would be to have
this voltage exceed

00:14:35.880 --> 00:14:39.150
this voltage by at least some
threshold voltage, nominally

00:14:39.150 --> 00:14:43.530
0.6 volts, which means that
the kind of relationship

00:14:43.530 --> 00:14:48.360
between v out and v in that you
would get is illustrated here.

00:14:48.360 --> 00:14:51.450
If the input voltage differed
from the output voltage

00:14:51.450 --> 00:14:54.480
by less than plus or minus
the threshold voltage, then

00:14:54.480 --> 00:14:57.070
nothing would happen because
neither transistor would be on.

00:14:59.760 --> 00:15:03.270
If the input exceeded what
was desired for the output

00:15:03.270 --> 00:15:06.150
by more than 0.6, the
transistor on the top

00:15:06.150 --> 00:15:10.960
would start to come on, and you
would get roughly linear growth

00:15:10.960 --> 00:15:14.830
in the output voltage in
relation to the input voltage.

00:15:14.830 --> 00:15:16.090
Similarly with negative.

00:15:16.090 --> 00:15:20.500
If you make the voltage at the
input sufficiently negative,

00:15:20.500 --> 00:15:22.010
you can cause the
bottom transistor

00:15:22.010 --> 00:15:26.636
to come on and suck the
voltage down toward minus 50.

00:15:26.636 --> 00:15:28.510
But again, you have to
exceed the difference.

00:15:28.510 --> 00:15:30.885
The difference has to exceed
something like the threshold

00:15:30.885 --> 00:15:34.960
voltage, normally about
0.6 volts, which means then

00:15:34.960 --> 00:15:39.280
that you get this piecewise
linear approximation

00:15:39.280 --> 00:15:43.400
to the relation between the
input and the output voltage.

00:15:43.400 --> 00:15:46.070
The problem with that is that
it distorts the waveform.

00:15:46.070 --> 00:15:49.040
So if I imagine a
purely sinusoidal input,

00:15:49.040 --> 00:15:53.720
what I get at the output then is
not a purely sinusoidal output.

00:15:53.720 --> 00:15:56.170
And, in fact, that's
quite objectionable

00:15:56.170 --> 00:15:57.760
for many purposes.

00:15:57.760 --> 00:15:59.560
In particular, in
the example where

00:15:59.560 --> 00:16:02.560
we're listening to a sound, if
we were to listen to this sound

00:16:02.560 --> 00:16:05.500
it would sound very
different from the way

00:16:05.500 --> 00:16:09.340
a sine wave would sound.

00:16:09.340 --> 00:16:11.350
So the way I can do that
is, not surprisingly,

00:16:11.350 --> 00:16:14.000
fix it with feedback.

00:16:14.000 --> 00:16:16.670
Again imagine that this
is the complicated part.

00:16:16.670 --> 00:16:19.230
v f naught, followed
by the speaker,

00:16:19.230 --> 00:16:22.030
put some gain in front
of it, gain's cheap.

00:16:22.030 --> 00:16:24.250
We can do that run
relatively well.

00:16:24.250 --> 00:16:26.320
And put in feedback
so that I can directly

00:16:26.320 --> 00:16:29.650
compare how is the speaker
voltage compare to the voltage

00:16:29.650 --> 00:16:32.440
that I'd like to listen to.

00:16:32.440 --> 00:16:35.380
The result then
is that, depending

00:16:35.380 --> 00:16:38.710
on how big is the
gain, I can change

00:16:38.710 --> 00:16:40.630
how big is this dead zone.

00:16:40.630 --> 00:16:47.060
The zone of input voltages that
produce no change in output.

00:16:47.060 --> 00:16:50.380
So if I turn up the gain, here
I am illustrating k equals one.

00:16:50.380 --> 00:16:53.680
If I turn it up to k equals two
the dead zone gets smaller--

00:16:53.680 --> 00:16:57.520
k equals four,
eight, 10, whatever.

00:16:57.520 --> 00:16:59.950
So the idea is that
by adjusting the gain,

00:16:59.950 --> 00:17:02.710
I control how much
feedback there is.

00:17:02.710 --> 00:17:07.410
And I can control how
distorted the wave form looks.

00:17:07.410 --> 00:17:11.910
And I can illustrate how
bad it is to not do that

00:17:11.910 --> 00:17:15.540
by comparing an
original clip of music

00:17:15.540 --> 00:17:17.550
to different values
of the feedback.

00:17:17.550 --> 00:17:20.670
So what I'm going to do
is play this many clips,

00:17:20.670 --> 00:17:22.920
some original--

00:17:22.920 --> 00:17:27.310
the original that
came off the mp3.

00:17:27.310 --> 00:17:29.310
Put it through the system
with no feedback, that

00:17:29.310 --> 00:17:30.660
is to say there isn't a k here.

00:17:30.660 --> 00:17:31.701
There's no feedback loop.

00:17:31.701 --> 00:17:35.220
You just put v in a v out.

00:17:35.220 --> 00:17:38.415
Then k of two, four, eight, 16,
and then back to the original.

00:17:38.415 --> 00:17:40.290
And if you listen, you
should be able to hear

00:17:40.290 --> 00:17:42.220
the effects of the distortion.

00:17:42.220 --> 00:17:42.720
OK.

00:17:42.720 --> 00:17:44.494
Ready?

00:17:44.494 --> 00:17:46.486
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:18:00.960 --> 00:18:01.590
You hear?

00:18:01.590 --> 00:18:03.586
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:19:05.471 --> 00:19:05.970
OK.

00:19:05.970 --> 00:19:07.840
Everybody get to hear it?

00:19:07.840 --> 00:19:10.510
So the point-- although the
acoustics in this room are

00:19:10.510 --> 00:19:12.130
terrible--

00:19:12.130 --> 00:19:16.480
but even somebody with
as old ears as mine, I

00:19:16.480 --> 00:19:19.610
can hear a very big
difference even between k

00:19:19.610 --> 00:19:23.230
equals 16 and the original if
I listen to it over headphones,

00:19:23.230 --> 00:19:25.630
or if I listen to it in
a better environment.

00:19:25.630 --> 00:19:27.680
So the point is that we're
very sensitive to it.

00:19:27.680 --> 00:19:29.630
In fact, 16 isn't even close.

00:19:29.630 --> 00:19:31.420
I mean, in a real
kind of an amplifier

00:19:31.420 --> 00:19:33.670
you would use gains
of at least 1,000

00:19:33.670 --> 00:19:35.620
in order to make it acceptable.

00:19:35.620 --> 00:19:38.900
So the point is that
we can use feedback.

00:19:38.900 --> 00:19:40.870
So the overall point
is to try to illustrate

00:19:40.870 --> 00:19:43.090
the kinds of things we
can do with feedback.

00:19:43.090 --> 00:19:45.700
Here what we're doing is making
a system that's intrinsically

00:19:45.700 --> 00:19:49.190
non-linear more linear.

00:19:52.210 --> 00:19:52.710
Questions?

00:19:52.710 --> 00:19:54.510
Comments?

00:19:54.510 --> 00:19:57.630
Left turn approaching.

00:19:57.630 --> 00:19:59.770
So what I want to
close with then

00:19:59.770 --> 00:20:02.610
is two more examples
that are much more fun.

00:20:02.610 --> 00:20:05.220
They're examples of
the use of feedback

00:20:05.220 --> 00:20:06.690
to stabilize unstable systems.

00:20:06.690 --> 00:20:09.390
This is kind of connecting
back to the very first lecture

00:20:09.390 --> 00:20:11.370
in this series that
Russ gave where

00:20:11.370 --> 00:20:14.010
he did some very
complicated control

00:20:14.010 --> 00:20:17.460
problems by doing feedback.

00:20:17.460 --> 00:20:19.330
I'm going to do some
slightly simpler ones.

00:20:19.330 --> 00:20:23.940
But they're hard
enough to be clear

00:20:23.940 --> 00:20:26.342
that they were a hard
problem, and easy enough

00:20:26.342 --> 00:20:28.800
that every one of you should
be able to write the equations

00:20:28.800 --> 00:20:31.789
and figure out what
I'm about to do.

00:20:31.789 --> 00:20:34.080
If you are interested to do
the more complicated things

00:20:34.080 --> 00:20:36.570
like having owls
come in and swoop,

00:20:36.570 --> 00:20:38.400
that's a research project.

00:20:38.400 --> 00:20:43.110
So this is supposed to be in the
middle ground between research

00:20:43.110 --> 00:20:44.670
and trivial, right?

00:20:44.670 --> 00:20:48.420
So I'm going to do some examples
now of some unstable systems

00:20:48.420 --> 00:20:54.200
to illustrate how you would
use feedback for stability.

00:20:54.200 --> 00:20:56.660
First example, is
magnetic levitation.

00:20:56.660 --> 00:20:58.700
You've probably heard
of magnetic levitation.

00:20:58.700 --> 00:21:00.170
Magnetic levitation is hard.

00:21:02.840 --> 00:21:05.390
We've talked about magnetic
levitation since the 70s

00:21:05.390 --> 00:21:07.760
at least, perhaps the 60s.

00:21:07.760 --> 00:21:10.580
It's hard because
magnetic systems tend

00:21:10.580 --> 00:21:12.090
to be intrinsically unstable.

00:21:12.090 --> 00:21:15.080
Not always, but
the easy ways you

00:21:15.080 --> 00:21:18.260
can imagine using a
magnet to levitate things.

00:21:18.260 --> 00:21:20.870
We'd all like to
make anti-grav right?

00:21:20.870 --> 00:21:23.810
Anti-grav would be
a really good thing.

00:21:23.810 --> 00:21:25.760
And it seems like you
ought to be able to do

00:21:25.760 --> 00:21:27.050
that with a magnet, right?

00:21:27.050 --> 00:21:31.010
So the idea is what I would
like to do is levitate

00:21:31.010 --> 00:21:35.470
a mass with a magnet.

00:21:35.470 --> 00:21:36.707
Anti-grav, right?

00:21:36.707 --> 00:21:38.290
We've had that since
Star Trek, right?

00:21:38.290 --> 00:21:39.460
It's time somebody built it.

00:21:39.460 --> 00:21:44.872
But it's hard even though
we can make magnets.

00:21:44.872 --> 00:21:46.330
Even though we can
make things that

00:21:46.330 --> 00:21:49.450
seemed like they would do it.

00:21:49.450 --> 00:21:53.110
It's hard because it's
intrinsically unstable.

00:21:53.110 --> 00:21:54.850
This particular system
is intrinsically

00:21:54.850 --> 00:21:58.360
unstable in the sense
that if the mass, let's

00:21:58.360 --> 00:22:02.170
say that it was at
equilibrium by which I mean,

00:22:02.170 --> 00:22:04.270
in the absence of
somebody touching it,

00:22:04.270 --> 00:22:06.100
it would stay exactly
the way it is.

00:22:06.100 --> 00:22:08.050
That's what I mean
by equilibrium.

00:22:08.050 --> 00:22:10.390
Let's say it was
at equilibrium so

00:22:10.390 --> 00:22:13.450
that the magnetic force I found
was just sufficient to hold up

00:22:13.450 --> 00:22:17.640
the weight, Mg.

00:22:17.640 --> 00:22:21.360
If I came over and
just very gently bumped

00:22:21.360 --> 00:22:26.045
the mass up a little, what
would happen to the force?

00:22:29.680 --> 00:22:30.577
Force will go up.

00:22:30.577 --> 00:22:32.785
So you're supposed to remember
this from some subject

00:22:32.785 --> 00:22:34.960
that you took before, right?

00:22:34.960 --> 00:22:36.290
Yes, no, yes?

00:22:36.290 --> 00:22:39.190
It started with an 8, yes?

00:22:39.190 --> 00:22:42.250
So the idea is something
to do with if you

00:22:42.250 --> 00:22:47.440
have a magnet of that type,
you generate magnetic fields.

00:22:47.440 --> 00:22:49.660
You remember they're not
supposed to cross, right?

00:22:49.660 --> 00:22:51.201
One of the rules is
they don't cross.

00:22:51.201 --> 00:22:53.170
[LAUGHTER]

00:22:53.170 --> 00:22:57.610
But the idea is that the
density of flux lines

00:22:57.610 --> 00:23:00.850
decreases as you
leave the magnet,

00:23:00.850 --> 00:23:02.830
and the force
that's generated has

00:23:02.830 --> 00:23:06.460
something to do with the change
in the density of flux lines.

00:23:06.460 --> 00:23:08.140
If you move an object
through a region

00:23:08.140 --> 00:23:10.056
where the number of flux
lines doesn't change,

00:23:10.056 --> 00:23:11.320
it takes no force.

00:23:11.320 --> 00:23:13.300
If you move an object
into a region that

00:23:13.300 --> 00:23:16.151
has fewer or more flux
lines, it requires force

00:23:16.151 --> 00:23:16.900
to make that move.

00:23:16.900 --> 00:23:18.400
That's the idea.

00:23:18.400 --> 00:23:24.250
So, since the flux lines are
thinning as you move away,

00:23:24.250 --> 00:23:26.837
if I push up it will generate--

00:23:26.837 --> 00:23:28.420
I'm moving the mass
into a place where

00:23:28.420 --> 00:23:32.110
there is a greater density of
flux lines, that will generate

00:23:32.110 --> 00:23:37.150
force up on the mass.

00:23:37.150 --> 00:23:40.240
That's bad, right?

00:23:40.240 --> 00:23:43.060
I had the force exactly where
I needed it to be in order

00:23:43.060 --> 00:23:44.782
to levitate the mass.

00:23:44.782 --> 00:23:46.240
If the force goes
up, what happens?

00:23:49.460 --> 00:23:50.870
It accelerates up.

00:23:50.870 --> 00:23:53.730
Well, OK, so it
accelerates up, then what?

00:23:53.730 --> 00:23:55.660
Well, it gets closer.

00:23:55.660 --> 00:23:57.510
Then what?

00:23:57.510 --> 00:24:00.640
It accelerates faster.

00:24:00.640 --> 00:24:05.950
So, the problem is that
the position is unstable,

00:24:05.950 --> 00:24:09.370
or we might say quasi stable.

00:24:09.370 --> 00:24:11.410
So what we can do is
make a model of this

00:24:11.410 --> 00:24:15.670
to try to understand how we
could fix it with feedback.

00:24:15.670 --> 00:24:17.560
Imagine that I
represent the magnet

00:24:17.560 --> 00:24:20.770
by a function that
maps for every value

00:24:20.770 --> 00:24:26.890
of the position of the mass
why it generates a force, f m.

00:24:26.890 --> 00:24:29.270
Then, because of the
shape of the field lines,

00:24:29.270 --> 00:24:31.805
I'm expecting that
the force increases

00:24:31.805 --> 00:24:33.430
on the right of the
curve and decreases

00:24:33.430 --> 00:24:36.010
on the left of the curve.

00:24:36.010 --> 00:24:40.630
If I'm sitting for y zero
at equilibrium what matters

00:24:40.630 --> 00:24:46.320
is the difference between y
and the equilibrium place.

00:24:46.320 --> 00:24:48.390
And the important
force is the difference

00:24:48.390 --> 00:24:53.220
between the magnetic
force and Mg, the weight.

00:24:53.220 --> 00:24:54.870
So I get a simple
relationship that

00:24:54.870 --> 00:24:59.010
says that this force,
this vertical line, f,

00:24:59.010 --> 00:25:02.040
should be m a.

00:25:02.040 --> 00:25:07.320
F equals m a which
is m y double dot.

00:25:07.320 --> 00:25:11.960
So having generated
that kind of a model

00:25:11.960 --> 00:25:15.780
I can now imagine putting
that into a feedback system.

00:25:15.780 --> 00:25:19.400
So now I put the model into the
feedback system and this junk

00:25:19.400 --> 00:25:23.400
over here, this is f equals m a.

00:25:23.400 --> 00:25:27.195
f gets multiplied by
one over m, that a.

00:25:27.195 --> 00:25:29.050
a is y double dot.

00:25:29.050 --> 00:25:30.500
Integrate it to get y dot.

00:25:30.500 --> 00:25:32.150
Integrate it again to get y.

00:25:32.150 --> 00:25:34.400
But y was the thing that
controlled the magnet

00:25:34.400 --> 00:25:37.170
in the first place.

00:25:37.170 --> 00:25:40.560
So I'm trying to cast magnetic
levitation into a frame

00:25:40.560 --> 00:25:42.030
for understanding feedback.

00:25:45.270 --> 00:25:48.690
So now if I want to
further simplify things

00:25:48.690 --> 00:25:54.330
I can replace the magnet model,
at least for small deviations

00:25:54.330 --> 00:25:58.059
in position, by a linear gain.

00:25:58.059 --> 00:25:59.850
So I'm making a straight
line approximation

00:25:59.850 --> 00:26:02.234
to this curvy line.

00:26:02.234 --> 00:26:03.650
And then we have
something that we

00:26:03.650 --> 00:26:06.140
analyze all the
time, simple feedback

00:26:06.140 --> 00:26:11.160
system that has integrators,
gains, that kind of stuff.

00:26:11.160 --> 00:26:15.590
It's surprisingly similar
to the mass spring dashpot.

00:26:15.590 --> 00:26:23.100
Springs, by contrast to magnets,
springs levitate stably.

00:26:23.100 --> 00:26:24.964
What happens if I
push-- so I'm suspending

00:26:24.964 --> 00:26:26.880
a mass from a spring,
if I push up on the mass

00:26:26.880 --> 00:26:29.700
how does the force
in the spring change?

00:26:29.700 --> 00:26:30.780
Gets less.

00:26:30.780 --> 00:26:33.000
That's what you want.

00:26:33.000 --> 00:26:35.970
It's no longer sufficient
to hold the mass up,

00:26:35.970 --> 00:26:38.040
so the mass falls.

00:26:38.040 --> 00:26:39.990
Push up, the mass tries to fall.

00:26:39.990 --> 00:26:43.880
Pull down on the mass,
